         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">1st January 1883 ¶ Dear Baron ¶  ¶ May this and many more years to come be full of happinness to you. I am glad to begin the new year, this early morning by writing to you. The letter will be accompan...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">83.01.01d</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Benedetto Scortechini</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M127, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Grevillea scortecinii</seg> spp <seg style="font-style: italic; ">scortechini</seg> (MEL 98955); M's label dated 1883 gives the taxon name as '<name key="Grevillea%20ilicifolia">Grevillea ilicifolia</name> Br. var. Scortechini'. MS annotation by M: 'Answ 9/1/83'. Letter not found.</p>
               </note>1st January 1883</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>May this and many more years to come be full of happinness to you. I am glad to begin the new year, this early morning by writing to you. The letter will be accompanied by a parcel of 25 plants, most of which are new to Q-land.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
               </note> You shall be able to mark the new stations in your <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">addenda</hi>
               </seg> to the census of all Australian species.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Presumably Scortechini knew or assumed that supplements would be produced to B83.03.04; no new <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Grevillea</seg> listings as Queensland species appeared until the fourth supplement, B89.05.03, p. 7.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Among these plants there is a Grevillea I have been unable to identify with any described one. I might have been too hasty in concluding it to be a new species. It has the aspect of G. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">laurina</hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Not in IPNI.</p>
               </note> with the leaves of G. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">ilicifolia</hi>
               </seg> and <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">repens</hi>
               </seg>. You will decide whether it is a new species, or new variety of one of these. Mr Bailey has got a set of all the plants I gathered in Stanthorpe<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
               </note> as there was a gentleman with me<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Henry Tryon? See F. Bailey to M, 19 May 1883 (in this edition as 83-05-19a).</p>
               </note> who was likewise gathering plants, and who gave them to Mr Bailey. I do not know what he made of this Grevillea, and of all others. If he coincides in my opinion that it is new he will publish it as such at once some where.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See F. Bailey to M, 16 January 1883 (in this edition as 83-01-16a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With many regards I remain</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your humble Servant</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B Scortechini</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="">What follows is on a separate slip of paper, also found with the specimen of </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Grevillea scortecinii</seg>
                     <seg style=""> spp </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">scortechini</seg>
                     <seg style=""> (MEL 98955) and numbered by Scortechini, '395'. It may not be part of the same letter.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>Grevillia n. sp?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: center; "
               xml:lang="en">Proteaceae</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Stanthorpe</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am strongly inclined to take it as a new species between G. laurifolia of the Blue Mountains,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>NSW.</p>
               </note> and your Victorian G. repens. Of both it has the prostate<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>prostrate?</p>
               </note> habit, gland, ovary, style and umbonate oblique stigmatic disk, and inflorescence. But in the shape and indumentum of the leaves it varies so much. I have no access to any specimens of G. repens, but from the description I can see to be very different, "sprinkled underneath with apressed hairs" Bentham says,<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 5, p. 437.</p>
               </note> whereas my specimens are closely silvery silky underneath. Then their geographical stations so far apart. No examination of the fruit has been made by me. You will find further discrepancies. It grows on granitic detritus</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Grevillea%20ilicifolia">Grevillea ilicifolia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Grevillea%20laurifolia">Grevillea laurifolia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Grevillea%20laurina">Grevillea laurina</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Grevillea%20repens">Grevillea repens</name>
            </p>
         </div>
